{"id":"2301.10005","submitter":"Jordan Morris","authors":"Jordan Morris and Ashur Rafiev and Graeme Bragg and Mark Vousden and\n  David Thomas and Alex Yakovlev and Andrew Brown","title":"An Event-Driven Approach To Genotype Imputation On A Custom RISC-V FPGA\n  Cluster","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This paper proposes an event-driven solution to genotype imputation, a\ntechnique used to statistically infer missing genetic markers in DNA. The work\nimplements the widely accepted Li and Stephens model, primary contributor to\nthe computational complexity of modern x86 solutions, in an attempt to\ndetermine whether further investigation of the application is warranted in the\nevent-driven domain. The model is implemented using graph-based Hidden Markov\nModeling and executed as a customized forward/backward dynamic programming\nalgorithm. The solution uses an event-driven paradigm to map the algorithm to\nthousands of concurrent cores, where events are small messages that carry both\ncontrol and data within the algorithm. The design of a single processing\nelement is discussed. This is then extended across multiple FPGAs and executed\non a custom RISC-V NoC FPGA cluster called POETS. Results demonstrate how the\nalgorithm scales over increasing hardware resources and a 48 FPGA run\ndemonstrates a 270X reduction in wall-clock processing time when compared to a\nsingle-threaded x86 solution. Optimisation of the algorithm via linear\ninterpolation is then introduced and tested, with results demonstrating a\nwall-clock reduction time of approx. 5 orders of magnitude when compared to a\nsimilarly optimised x86 solution.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 22 Jan 2023 22:09:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-25"}
